I've been to several fine restaurant around the world. From Tetsuya, Quay, Sepia, Dinner by heston, and netflix's attica. I never have been so disappoint with the food. I guess price don't lie since the price lies with the cheaper side of fine dining.

2.5/5 Short Version: Food was average and unmemorable (not the best $120+ I've spent). Service was as expected but the bread man drove us crazy (somehow bread kept appearing on our small plates). I probably wouldn't go out of my way to return. ---- A friend was in town and she wanted to get a group together to dine at Gary Danko. I had never been so seized on the opportunity. After all, this is one of the most reviewed restaurants on Yelp SF! Our reservation was at 8:30pm for dinner and after check in we were told to wait at the bar for a couple minutes (during we each ordered a cocktail). Once the table was ready we were ready to dine. I went with the three dish option ($83). Note if you order all apps or entrees, they will size your 2nd or 3rd course appropriately so that it's a 'full size'. For example, I had my beef as the 3rd course and it was maybe 1/3 larger than my friend who had it as a 2nd course. This actually made a difference because my filet had a better sear and more rare center. Seared Foie Gras with Caramelized Onions and Apples - Delicious, rich foie but there were some unsavory bits that probably could have been cut off. I liked the pairing with onion and fruit; however, the microgreens(?) on the side were unnecessary. Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Blood Oranges, Edamame and Basil - Well cooked but the lobster was TINY. I didn't know lobsters existed that small. I had perhaps a tsp of edamame and basil and didn't taste the blood orange. The potato puree was the best part. Seared Filet of Beef with Potato Gnocchi, Olive Oil, Swiss Chard and Stilton Butter - The meat was well cooked -- crisp sear and rare center; however the texture of the meat itself wasn't very smooth (maybe it was a bit dried out) Bread served on the side with room-temp butter - Pretty boring. it was like soft sliced bread and the butter could have been slightly more salted. Hemingway Dacquiri ($13) - This was mostly rum and grapefruit juice if I recall correctly. The flavors were good but the drink itself was too sweet for me. Banana Cake/Muffin (freebie with meal) - Moist with a strong banana flavor. My favorite was the foie but mostly because I just like foie. The dishes were plated neatly and executed well but had unmemorable flavors. Maybe I ordered the wrong things--but I tried my friends' stuffed quail (couldn't find the foie that was stuffed inside), crab salad (not enough acid), duck (the duck was very well cooked but the flavors were too smokey and sides were average). I know people often associate 'classic' with 'boring' but I was at Le Bernardin just a few weeks ago (classic french) and found it much more delicious. Finally, regarding the service/environment, it was as expected for a fine dining restaurant. They have a coat check, but it's basically a rack of hooks behind the hostess booth. The dining tables seemed a little close together. Also, we regularly had to stop the the bread server from leaving bread on our plates (I know people rave about keeping wine glasses topped off, but we really don't need that much bread -- at least ask first). Also, I wish they brought the amuse (1oz of a fruit gazpacho )after we ordered -- it set a tone that felt a bit rushed.

Absolutely amazing. Although this review is long overdue, Gary Danko left me with a unforgettable experience with it's exquisite and delicious food, beautiful decor, warm ambiance, and attentive service. My boyfriend and I opted for the 5-course meal. Tons of food, considering they also give small complimentary side dishes too :). Everything tasted great, but our top three items were the Risotto, Roast Maine Lobster, and the Seared Filet of Beef. The real winner of the night was the Chocolate Soufflé. It had a delicious melted chocolate center and a light, airy exterior. It was chocolate heaven from the inside out! After coming here, I have high expectations for every fine dining restaurant I go to. So far, nothing compares to Gary Danko.

I've now celebrated two very special occasions at Gary Danko and am ready to throw my own five star into the masses they've accrued over the years. There are plenty of other reviews you can read if you want to understand the dining format so I'll try to stick with why I return myself: Service here is impeccable. The waitstaff knows the menu in crazy detail and will happily spend upwards of thirty minutes consulting with you, if you'd like. They're also completely prepared to be more or less invisible if you prefer that kind of service. The website gives you an option to fax in a credit card if you want the payment process to be completely seamless and you can also arrange for champagne or gifts to be presented at the beginning or end of your meal ahead of time. I was amazed to find that in four years, the price had only increased $5 for their five course meal. $124 is a steal when you consider the premium quality of the ingredients, excellent preparation and essentially, that you can order five full entrees if you so please. (We did, this most recent time and left feeling so full it hurt) Two types of foie gras. Both delicious. Nuff said. Cocktails are $12 apiece which in today's SF market is very reasonable. They are well made, if not particularly inventive. Wine list is extensive. The special complimentary touches! That little dish of desserts at the end of the meal isn't delicious on its own merits but it's free and has an interesting assortment of bites to finish your meal. If you are special occasioning (which it seems like almost everyone is) there's a nicely plated dessert with an inscription of what you are celebrating. The light banana cake treat with cream cheese frosting is a lovely parting gift and more restaurants should do that! Strangely, don't come here for the ambience. It's somewhere between a cruise and a wedding where everyone is sitting too close together, no views, natural light or particularly beautiful decorations to speak of.

If Gary Danko (the restaurant, not the man himself) was a man, I would imagine him as Sean Connery. Strong, charming, classy, and kicks ass. I was taken here by the girlfriend for my birthday (I am spoiled). The moment you walk into the restaurant you get the one star Michelin service. Our coats were taken, the table was pulled out for us to sit and our amuse bouche was brought out (a delicious cream soup). We were given a moment to take a look at our menus and settle into to the space. The dining room has a very classic 90's fine dining experience. Dated but charming none the less. The hardest decision you'll have to make that night is what you want to eat. Gary Danko throws back to my childhood and lets you select your meal Choose Your Own Adventure style. They have a set list of 20+ courses ranging from appetizers, seafood, entree (meats!), to desserts. You pick a 3, 4, or 5 course meal and choose any course you wish for. If you pick a 5 course meal you can pick 5 desserts or 5 lobsters if you wanted. I opted for a 5 course meal of all savory dishes and I forced my girlfriend to order 4 courses so I can try the dishes that didn't quite make it into my top 5 dish list. We know nothing about wine, but since it was a special occasion we decided to get a glass. The sommelier suggested us glasses that would work with the dishes we selected. I thought it would be tough as I got something from every spectrum of the menu, but he picked out affordable glasses for us wine noobs. For the beginning of the meal we started with a crispy egg and crab salad. The crispy egg was perfectly poached and fried in bread crumbs over mushrooms and polenta. Just watching the egg yolk ooze onto everything else was worth the meal. The crab salad was excellent, but my egg out shined it. Next out was a crab and mushroom risotto, sea bass, and lobster tail. All the dishes were well prepared perfectly, but the lobster stood out the most. I felt the other dishes I could experience at any other fine dining restaurant, but the lobster was buttery smooth and full of flavor. When we both took a bite, all we could say was wow. The main courses made their way out and our jaw dropped as the duck breast, beef fillet, and stuffed quail came out. We had no clue how we were going to have room for all these dishes, but we sucked it up and started eat. First world problems. The duck was served in two ways - a lemon pepper duck breast on top of a celery garlic root purée with crispy duck has. I could have stopped here but I still had a beef fillet to tackle. The fillet was cooked perfectly to medium rare with a savory shallot marmalade next to swiss chard. The stuffed quail was packed full of flavor and probably would have been my favorite if not for the many of dishes before. To end the meal on a decadent not, I was brought out a chocolate mousse birthday cake along my girlfriend's trio of crème brulee with assorted cookies. Yes, you heard right, a trio as in three crème brulees. Just when I thought we had all our dishes the staff brought out a platter of assorted bite size desserts. The chocolate birthday cake was rich as F, but delicious non the less. After we worked our way through the pile of desserts, we were left with the bill and individual pumpkin bread with a cheesecake topping for the next morning. Gary Danko knows how to treat us right. The food was text book fancy. The service swept us off our feet. We left more than satisfied and indulged.

I can't believe I found an empty, unfinished review on my yelp listings. I am not the sort of food savant who can recall every detail of a dinner nearly nine months later. However, my wife and I both recall an extraordinary meal, gracious service, a beautiful restaurant, seeing an original painting by one of our favorite artists and a wonderful way to close our visit to California and SF.

The food: -Tip: With the set-course menu, you can choose any number of dishes from each section of the menu. If you're hungry and want the best bang for your buck, skip the appetizers and desserts and get 3 entrees (assuming you chose the 3-course menu). You can get the prepared table side dessert for an extra $6. -Overall opinion: You MUST try this restaurant! The food is just perfect. You can't go wrong with any dish. I give this place a 5/5 rating because they couldn't have made any dish any better. -On the house to start: Miso Soup. Small portion of the soup to cleanse the pallet. Stock is more of a soy sauce base rather than miso paste. -the butter that came with the bread was very rich and aromatic- loved it! You get an endless supply of bread. If there's any less than 2 slices at any given time on your plate, the waiters will top you up unless as long as your bread plate is still on the table -sea bass was perfect. The skin was lightly crispy and the meat inside was juicy. The bed of vegetables was just lovely. One of the best, if not THE best, prepared sea bass I've ever had. Wish the portion size was a bit larger! -risotto was very creamy and rich -lobster was just perfect. Soft and delicate -Thai coconut curry was light and did not over power the taste of the seafood; seafood was cooked just right (not over-cooked) and it was a generous portion of scallops and lobster -the salmon was probably my least favourite as it was a bit over cooked but it was still enjoyable -the scallops were perfect; they were under-cooked but the texture was great and the flavour came through; the size of the scallops were very large! -grand mariner soufflé has been the best soufflé I've ever had - so light and fluffy like an uncle Tetsu cheesecake with delightful hints of marmalade and a thin layer of hard caramel on top similar to a creme brûlée -water and bread is always refilled -petite fours are served at the end and they give you a serving of banana bread to take home The service: -As you would expect from a high-end restaurant, staff are very formal, professional, and attentive. Your glass of water will always be topped up. There are plenty of staff members around to help you at any given time -Meals always came out at the same time for the entire table and each dish was properly explained -Good amount of time elapsed between courses to give you time to digest and talk (my husband was hungry so he kept eating the bottomless bread!) -Give yourself 2.5-3 hours at the restaurant -I was very satisfied with the service The ambiance: -It's a nice restaurant with three sections (I think, I didn't walk around). I was lucky enough to get seated against the side of the restaurant facing the bar and facing everyone else in my section so I could see everything that was going on. Even luckier was being seated right in front of Carlos Santana that night :) -While it's an upscale restaurant, it didn't feel stuffy and despite my more casual attire (I wasn't completely casual but I wasn't dressed to the nines), it wasn't frowned upon nor did I feel out of place. Most women wore a dress and men in suits or a dress shirt. My only feedback for improvement: -I have no complaints about the ambiance, service or food. The only suggestion I have (and I only noticed this because my arse was killing me from a day of biking) is that the seats could've been more comfortable (I sat in a booth). I could feel discomfort during dinner, especially when I went home sitting in the back seat of a Prius Uber and felt the comparison was so much better!

Dining at Gary Danko is an event! Expect outstanding food, attentive service, servers with great knowledge about the food and to stuff your bellies! What can I say about the food that hasn't already been said? This is not the type of fancy restaurant where you will go away still hungry. I felt barely able to walk after the 4-course meal. And they give you something for the next morning as well! You will go away feeling that what you paid was well-worth the cost. Highlights for me were the butterfly-shaped ahi tuna appetizer and the amazing cheese selection for the cheese course! This is not someplace you can come every week (unless you're a Silicon Valley CEO or the like) but for a special occasion, this is definitely at the top of my list. And of course, I don't need to tell you this but you will need to make reservations at least 1-2 months in advance!

I love the concept of Gary Danko's tasting menu. You choose 3, 4, or 5 courses (priced at $83, $101, and $119) and from there, you can choose whatever combination of appetizers, entrees, and desserts you like. Being gluttons (and in celebration of my birthday), me and my dining companion each chose 5 courses. I recommend NOT doing this because 1. it's wayyy too much food (that's saying a lot coming from me) and 2. the heavier entree dishes that are served towards the end are not as great. Given that we had 10 dishes to pick, we literally tried everything on their menu. I loved the appetizers. The glazed oyster tasted like heaven. and sex. I want to bathe in a tub filled with that lettuce cream. Or a tub of their risotto with shimeji mushrooms. Scallops were pretty on point too. Unfortunately, having grown up with Asian parents that tell you to get your moneys worth by eating the most expensive items, we over-ordered on the meat and game bird dishes. These dishes fell short of my expectations. Red meats should always be rare to medium-rare and both my bison and steak tasted a bit dry. Alongside our ordered desserts, we were also given a platter of little treats (petit fours), a complimentary chocolate souffle, and banana bread to go. What a nice touch! Service was impeccable and we did not feel rushed even after eating for over 3 hours. We sat next to a rowdy table but they bought us shots of Fernet so cheers to that! Overall, Gary Danko is great bang for your buck! Ok, not in the same sense as Micky D's obviously, but definitely good value for a michelin star restaurant. You can easily have a delicious (and filling) 3 course fine dining experience here for less than $120 per person. TL:DR Great experience. Tasty food with sizable portions. Don't order meat. Pro tip -- Only order 3 courses and just eat your free desserts.

Gary Danko has always been THE special place for us to go to when we want to celebrate special events. So when it came time to celebrate our once-in-a-lifetime 30 year anniversary, we didn't even have to think about it. Of course, we would go to Gary Danko. We couldn't wait to make the reservation 30 days ahead and then counted the days, hours, and minutes until the special moment arrived. We could not have been more disappointed with our experience. WE COULD NOT HAVE BEEN MORE DISAPPOINTED WITH OUR EXPERIENCE AT GARY DANKO. We walked in the door at EXACTLY 6:30PM (the EXACT time of our reservation). The unfriendly / uncaring hostess said we would need to "step over there" for awhile because our table wasn't ready. Hmmmm.... We saw several empty tables and, in fact, one of those was ours -- but we weren't "allowed" to sit there until 10 minutes later. That didn't make any sense to us, but we said to ourselves, we're at Gary Danko, the best of the best, let the fun begin. Once FINALLY seated, we waited for 10 minutes before ANYone came to our table. We ordered cocktails, which came at least 15 minutes later. This set the tone for the entire rest of the night: loooooooong waits between EVERYthing became what the evening was all about. We each ordered 5 courses. They were big about saying: "You can each order any number of courses, whatever you want." We each ordered wine pairing with each of our courses. For the first course, we got the wine pairing and then waited, waited, waited for the first course to arrive. Then we waited, waited, waited some more. The first course arrived maybe 20 minutes after we got the first course's wine pairing. There wasn't much left of the wine to pair with the first course. But nobody bothered to notice or care. For the second course, we got the second course and then LITERALLY HAD TO WAVE SOMEONE DOWN to bring the wine pairing to our table. WE HAD TO WAVE SOMEONE DOWN. We were at Gary Danko. When was the last time you had to WAVE SOMEONE DOWN at Gary Danko? Things got even worse after that. The third course arrived for ONE of us, with wine pairing. (Remember, we each ordered 5 courses with wine pairing). So ONE of us ate and drank a third course for 20 minutes while the other of us sat and watched. Then, UNBELIEVABLY, the 4th course arrived for the same person who got the 3rd course -- while the other person, ONCE AGAIN, sat with NOTHING to eat or drink. One person essentially ate and drank for about 45 minutes while the other person sat there and watched. Think about that. We were both dumbstruck. We complained and had several people come and talk down to us to explain that even though we had each ordered 5 courses, apparently they weren't all to arrive at the same time. So we astonishingly asked, "What on earth are you talking about? You have designed this experience to result in a dinner where one person eats while the other doesn't eat or drink anything? For nearly an hour? Really?" The answer, quite honestly, was, "Yes, and it's your fault -- you ordered it this way." I would accept that answer at, say, Olive Garden -- but at GARY DANKO??????? I don't think so. So of course the 4th and 5th courses arrived for the OTHER person while I had nothing to eat. The whole experience made no sense whatsoever. Even the people at the closely-packed tables on either side of us watched with bewilderment and felt compelled to ask us, "What happened?!?" Not once did either of us ever think that ordering 5 courses (the most you could order) would result in each of us essentially eating most of our dinner by ourselves while the other one watched. We live in San Francisco and go to restaurants for most of our meals. Here's what I think is happening at Gary Danko. They are phoning it in. They are coasting on their reputation of being a remarkable restaurant. In all of our many many times of eating at Gary Danko, they were incredibly remarkable in every possible way. Tonight was a ghastly departure from that. Every single thing about the experience was mediocre (and, frankly, ridiculous). The bread was clearly yesterday's dry stale bread. The butter was served ice cold (WHY?). There were those unacceptably long waits between courses. And not to be forgotten, I used the washroom right before the first course FINALLY arrived, and the washroom was disgusting -- pee all over the floor and what was in the toilet had not been flushed. When I revisited that same bathroom an hour later, the same pee was all over the floor, the toilet seat was likewise covered in pee (ewww), and the whole room smelled VILE. Utterly disgusting. Very disappointing evening, the last possible thing we expected for tonight.

    A friend was in town and she wanted to get a group together to dine at Gary Danko. I had never been so seized on the opportunity. After all, this is one of the most reviewed restaurants on Yelp SF! Our reservation was at 8:30pm for dinner and after check in we were told to wait at the bar for a couple minutes (during we each ordered a cocktail). Once the table was ready we were ready to dine. I went with the three dish option ($83). Note if you order all apps or entrees, they will size your 2nd or 3rd course appropriately so that it's a 'full size'. For example, I had my beef as the 3rd course and it was maybe 1/3 larger than my friend who had it as a 2nd course. This actually made a difference because my filet had a better sear and more rare center.

    Seared Foie Gras with Caramelized Onions and Apples
    - Delicious, rich foie but there were some unsavory bits that probably could have been cut off. I liked the pairing with onion and fruit; however, the microgreens(?) on the side were unnecessary.

    Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Blood Oranges, Edamame and Basil
    - Well cooked but the lobster was TINY. I didn't know lobsters existed that small. I had perhaps a tsp of edamame and basil and didn't taste the blood orange. The potato puree was the best part.

    Seared Filet of Beef with Potato Gnocchi, Olive Oil, Swiss Chard and Stilton Butter
    - The meat was well cooked -- crisp sear and rare center; however the texture of the meat itself wasn't very smooth (maybe it was a bit dried out)

    Bread served on the side with room-temp butter
    - Pretty boring. it was like soft sliced bread and the butter could have been slightly more salted.

    Hemingway Dacquiri ($13)
    - This was mostly rum and grapefruit juice if I recall correctly. The flavors were good but the drink itself was too sweet for me.

    Banana Cake/Muffin (freebie with meal)
    - Moist with a strong banana flavor.

    My favorite was the foie but mostly because I just like foie. The dishes were plated neatly and executed well but had unmemorable flavors. Maybe I ordered the wrong things--but I tried my friends' stuffed quail (couldn't find the foie that was stuffed inside), crab salad (not enough acid), duck (the duck was very well cooked but the flavors were too smokey and sides were average). I know people often associate 'classic' with 'boring' but I was at Le Bernardin just a few weeks ago (classic french) and found it much more delicious.

    Finally, regarding the service/environment, it was as expected for a fine dining restaurant. They have a coat check, but it's basically a rack of hooks behind the hostess booth. The dining tables seemed a little close together. Also, we regularly had to stop the the bread server from leaving bread on our plates (I know people rave about keeping wine glasses topped off, but we really don't need that much bread -- at least ask first). Also, I wish they brought the amuse (1oz of a fruit gazpacho )after we ordered --  it set a tone that felt a bit rushed.

    I've now celebrated two very special occasions at Gary Danko and am ready to throw my own five star into the masses they've accrued over the years.

    There are plenty of other reviews you can read if you want to understand the dining format so I'll try to stick with why I return myself:

    Service here is impeccable. The waitstaff knows the menu in crazy detail and will happily spend upwards of thirty minutes consulting with you, if you'd like. They're also completely prepared to be more or less invisible if you prefer that kind of service. The website gives you an option to fax in a credit card if you want the payment process to be completely seamless and you can also arrange for champagne or gifts to be presented at the beginning or end of your meal ahead of time.

    I was amazed to find that in four years, the price had only increased $5 for their five course meal. $124 is a steal when you consider the premium quality of the ingredients, excellent preparation and essentially, that you can order five full entrees if you so please. (We did, this most recent time and left feeling so full it hurt)

    Two types of foie gras. Both delicious. Nuff said.

    Cocktails are $12 apiece which in today's SF market is very reasonable. They are well made, if not particularly inventive. Wine list is extensive.

    The special complimentary touches! That little dish of desserts at the end of the meal isn't delicious on its own merits but it's free and has an interesting assortment of bites to finish your meal. If you are special occasioning (which it seems like almost everyone is) there's a nicely plated dessert with an inscription of what you are celebrating. The light banana cake treat with cream cheese frosting is a lovely parting gift and more restaurants should do that!

    Strangely, don't come here for the ambience. It's somewhere between a cruise and a wedding where everyone is sitting too close together, no views, natural light or particularly beautiful decorations to speak of.

    If Gary Danko (the restaurant, not the man himself) was a man, I would imagine him as Sean Connery. Strong, charming, classy, and kicks ass.

    I was taken here by the girlfriend for my birthday (I am spoiled). The moment you walk into the restaurant you get the one star Michelin service. Our coats were taken, the table was pulled out for us to sit and our amuse bouche was brought out (a delicious cream soup). We were given a moment to take a look at our menus and settle into to the space. The dining room has a very classic 90's fine dining experience. Dated but charming none the less.

    The hardest decision you'll have to make that night is what you want to eat. Gary Danko throws back to my childhood and lets you select your meal Choose Your Own Adventure style. They have a set list of 20+ courses ranging from appetizers, seafood, entree (meats!), to desserts. You pick a 3, 4, or 5 course meal and choose any course you wish for. If you pick a 5 course meal you can pick 5 desserts or 5 lobsters if you wanted. I opted for a 5 course meal of all savory dishes and I forced my girlfriend to order 4 courses so I can try the dishes that didn't quite make it into my top 5 dish list.

    We know nothing about wine, but since it was a special occasion we decided to get a glass. The sommelier suggested us glasses that would work with the dishes we selected. I thought it would be tough as I got something from every spectrum of the menu, but he picked out affordable glasses for us wine noobs.

    For the beginning of the meal we started with a crispy egg and crab salad. The crispy egg was perfectly poached and fried in bread crumbs over mushrooms and polenta. Just watching the egg yolk ooze onto everything else was worth the meal. The crab salad was excellent, but my egg out shined it.

    Next out was a crab and mushroom risotto, sea bass, and lobster tail. All the dishes were well prepared perfectly, but the lobster stood out the most. I felt the other dishes I could experience at any other fine dining restaurant, but the lobster was buttery smooth and full of flavor. When we both took a bite, all we could say was wow.

    The main courses made their way out and our jaw dropped as the duck breast, beef fillet, and stuffed quail came out. We had no clue how we were going to have room for all these dishes, but we sucked it up and started eat. First world problems. The duck was served in two ways - a lemon pepper duck breast on top of a celery garlic root purée with crispy duck has. I could have stopped here but I still had a beef fillet to tackle. The fillet was cooked perfectly to medium rare with a savory shallot marmalade next to swiss chard. The stuffed quail was packed full of flavor and probably would have been my favorite if not for the many of dishes before.

    To end the meal on a decadent not, I was brought out a chocolate mousse birthday cake along my girlfriend's trio of crème brulee with assorted cookies. Yes, you heard right, a trio as in three crème brulees. Just when I thought we had all our dishes the staff brought out a platter of assorted bite size desserts. The chocolate birthday cake was rich as F, but delicious non the less.

    After we worked our way through the pile of desserts, we were left with the bill and individual pumpkin bread with a cheesecake topping for the next morning. Gary Danko knows how to treat us right.

    The food was text book fancy. The service swept us off our feet. We left more than satisfied and indulged.

    The food:
    -Tip: With the set-course menu, you can choose any number of dishes from each section of the menu. If you're hungry and want the best bang for your buck, skip the appetizers and desserts and get 3 entrees (assuming you chose the 3-course menu). You can get the prepared table side dessert for an extra $6.
    -Overall opinion: You MUST try this restaurant! The food is just perfect. You can't go wrong with any dish. I give this place a 5/5 rating because they couldn't have made any dish any better.
    -On the house to start: Miso Soup. Small portion of the soup to cleanse the pallet. Stock is more of a soy sauce base rather than miso paste.
    -the butter that came with the bread was very rich and aromatic- loved it! You get an endless supply of bread. If there's any less than 2 slices at any given time on your plate, the waiters will top you up unless as long as your bread plate is still on the table
    -sea bass was perfect. The skin was lightly crispy and the meat inside was juicy. The bed of vegetables was just lovely. One of the best, if not THE best, prepared sea bass I've ever had. Wish the portion size was a bit larger!
    -risotto was very creamy and rich
    -lobster was just perfect. Soft and delicate
    -Thai coconut curry was light and did not over power the taste of the seafood; seafood was cooked just right (not over-cooked) and it was a generous portion of scallops and lobster
    -the salmon was probably my least favourite as it was a bit over cooked but it was still enjoyable
    -the scallops were perfect; they were under-cooked but the texture was great and the flavour came through; the size of the scallops were very large!
    -grand mariner soufflé has been the best soufflé I've ever had - so light and fluffy like an uncle Tetsu cheesecake with delightful hints of marmalade and a thin layer of hard caramel on top similar to a creme brûlée
    -water and bread is always refilled
    -petite fours are served at the end and they give you a serving of banana bread to take home

    The service:
    -As you would expect from a high-end restaurant, staff are very formal, professional, and attentive. Your glass of water will always be topped up. There are plenty of staff members around to help you at any given time
    -Meals always came out at the same time for the entire table and each dish was properly explained
    -Good amount of time elapsed between courses to give you time to digest and talk (my husband was hungry so he kept eating the bottomless bread!)
    -Give yourself 2.5-3 hours at the restaurant
    -I was very satisfied with the service

    The ambiance:
    -It's a nice restaurant with three sections (I think, I didn't walk around). I was lucky enough to get seated against the side of the restaurant facing the bar and facing everyone else in my section so I could see everything that was going on. Even luckier was being seated right in front of Carlos Santana that night :)
    -While it's an upscale restaurant, it didn't feel stuffy and despite my more casual attire (I wasn't completely casual but I wasn't dressed to the nines), it wasn't frowned upon nor did I feel out of place. Most women wore a dress and men in suits or a dress shirt.

    My only feedback for improvement:
    -I have no complaints about the ambiance, service or food. The only suggestion I have (and I only noticed this because my arse was killing me from a day of biking) is that the seats could've been more comfortable (I sat in a booth). I could feel discomfort during dinner, especially when I went home sitting in the back seat of a Prius Uber and felt the comparison was so much better!

    I love the concept of Gary Danko's tasting menu. You choose 3, 4, or 5 courses (priced at $83, $101, and $119) and from there, you can choose whatever combination of appetizers, entrees, and desserts you like. Being gluttons (and in celebration of my birthday), me and my dining companion each chose 5 courses.     Given that we had 10 dishes to pick, we literally tried everything on their menu. I loved the appetizers. The glazed oyster tasted like heaven. and sex. I want to bathe in a tub filled with that lettuce cream. Or a tub of their risotto with shimeji mushrooms. Scallops were pretty on point too.

    Unfortunately, having grown up with Asian parents that tell you to get your moneys worth by eating the most expensive items, we over-ordered on the meat and game bird dishes. These dishes fell short of my expectations. Red meats should always be rare to medium-rare and both my bison and steak tasted a bit dry.

    Alongside our ordered desserts, we were also given a platter of little treats (petit fours), a complimentary chocolate souffle, and banana bread to go. What a nice touch!

    Service was impeccable and we did not feel rushed even after eating for over 3 hours. We sat next to a rowdy table but they bought us shots of Fernet so cheers to that!

    Overall, Gary Danko is great bang for your buck! Ok, not in the same sense as Micky D's obviously, but definitely good value for a michelin star restaurant. You can easily have a delicious (and filling) 3 course fine dining experience here for less than $120 per person.

    TL:DR Great experience. Tasty food with sizable portions. Don't order meat.
    Pro tip -- Only order 3 courses and just eat your free desserts.

    Seared scallop~I love scallops so I thought this dish was delicious. I wish there were more than 2 pieces though :(
    Roasted quail~I was full by the time this dish came out but it was still good
    Herb crusted loin of lamb~cooked nicely and tasted amazing
    Juniper crusted bison~I've never had bison before and this was great. It was seasoned well and it melted in my mouth
    (There was one more dish but I forgot what it was...)

    For desserts, we got:
    Lemon soufflé cake~first time eating a soufflé and it was good. I enjoyed the raspberry sorbet that came with it even more

    We also ordered drinks but I forgot what it's called. There was one non alcoholic lavender drink that I loved. I want another one of that drink right now!

    They also gave us each a pineapple breakfast pastry and it was sooooo good. I wanted another one.

    The service was on point!
